e district, Kent, England":"Lympne, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1530–":"1530–Deceased","1520–1559":"1520–1559","1530–Male":"1530–Deceased","1530–1625":"1530–1625","1565–1625":"1565–1625","1515–1575":"1515–1575","–Female":"Deceased","1571":"1571","13 October 1563":"13 October 1563","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1565":"1565","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1575":"1575","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1651":"1651","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","1625":"1625","1559":"1559","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Lympne, Folkestone and Hythe district, Kent, England":"Lympne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robbins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Robin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Robin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Andre, Emile, Marcel, Achille, Armand, Arnaud, Camille, Julien, Michel, Normand.","French, Breton, Scottish, English, and German: from the personal name <i>Robin</i>, a pet form of   Robert  , composed of the short form <i>Rob</i> + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-in</i>.","Slovenian: topographic name derived from <i>rob</i> ‘edge, border’ (see   Robar  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":19,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":28,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":39,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":41,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":70,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":90,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":112,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas B. Robbins was born in 1530, in Lympne, Kent, England as the son of Frank O. Robbins and Elizabeth Joan Palmer. He married Ida Ann Stobaugh on 13 October 1563, in Lympne, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1530–":"1530–Surnud","1520–1559":"1520–1559","1530–Male":"1530–Surnud","1530–1625":"1530–1625","1565–1625":"1565–1625","1515–1575":"1515–1575","–Female":"Surnud","1571":"1571","13 October 1563":"13. oktoober 1563","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1565":"1565","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1575":"1575","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1651":"1651","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","1625":"1625","1559":"1559","Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Lympne, Folkestone and Hythe district, Kent, England":"Lympne, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1530–":"1530–Kuollut","1520–1559":"1520–15